				\begin{document}$$\:\ge\:\:$$\end{document} 6 7 8 9 12 Over the years, various tools have been developed to screen or evaluate frailty, yet none has become a universal standard. The Fried frailty phenotype (FP) relies on objective measures like grip strength, making it impractical for large-scale population studies or busy clinical environments [ 13 15 16 18 19 21 22 23 In China, the challenge is compounded by the use of frailty tools translated from foreign languages, which often fail to reflect local cultural contexts [ 24 25 26 28 29 30 31 32 33 Currently, China lacks a locally developed, multi-dimensional, and brief frailty screening tool suited for community use [ 24 25 32 33 Methods This study utilized a multi-round Delphi consensus method for the development of a frailty screening scale. Establishment of a study group There were eight members in the study group, including one professor of evidence-based medicine, two professors of geriatrics, and five graduate students. All members were involved in geriatrics, clinical research methodology, or evidence-based medicine. Their responsibilities included literature search, preliminary item construction, expert recruitment, questionnaire development and administration, as well as data analysis and finalization of the scale. Prepare a questionnaire Build the pool of items The questionnaire was designed to develop a culturally appropriate frailty screening scale for community-dwelling older adults in China. We began by conducting a systematic review and meta-analysis (PROSPERO registration number: CRD42023415074) to identify existing frailty assessment tools and extract high-frequency, high-relevance items associated with multiple frailty domains, including physical, psychological, cognitive, nutritional, and social aspects. This literature-informed item pool served as the foundation for further refinement through expert consensus. This preliminary pool was then reviewed by selected experts for relevance evaluation using the Delphi method.To ensure contextual relevance, we sought input from experienced geriatricians, public health specialists, clinical epidemiologists, and community healthcare professionals. These experts were invited to evaluate and provide feedback on the appropriateness of each item in the context of Chinese older adults living in community settings. The initial pool of potential items included both observable indicators such as gait speed, weight loss and subjective reports such as fatigue, emotional well-being, reflecting the multidimensional aspects of frailty. Each item was rated using a 5-point Likert scale based on its perceived importance for screening frailty in community settings. Experts were encouraged to comment on the clarity, feasibility, and cultural applicability of each item. In Round 1, all items were retained regardless of their score to collect qualitative feedback. Based on expert comments, some items were revised and resubmitted in Round 2 for further evaluation. Screening of correspondence experts The Delphi method obtains expert feedback through repeated rounds of questionnaires to reach a structured, representative consensus. Experts were selected through purposive sampling based on their experience in frailty research and relevance to community healthcare in China. The inclusion criteria for experts were as follows: (1) holding a bachelor’s degree or higher; (2) possessing a senior or middle-level professional title; (3) having at least 10 years of experience in geriatrics, public health, community care, or evidence-based medicine; (4) willingness to participate voluntarily; and (5) representing a variety of disciplinary backgrounds and geographic regions. Experts were excluded if they: (1) completed the questionnaires perfunctorily or with missing key information; (2) failed to respond within the required time frame; or (3) showed limited engagement across Delphi rounds. Design expert inquiry form The expert inquiry form consisted of three main components: (1) a general description of the study purpose and the background of frailty screening in community-dwelling older adults in China; (2) the core content of the scale items, including item descriptions, importance rating criteria, and scoring instructions; and (3) collection of expert demographic and professional background information. Each item was rated on a 5-point Likert scale (1 = not important, 5 = very important). Experts were encouraged to provide qualitative feedback in the comment section, including suggestions for modification, addition, or removal of items, along with their rationale. Expert characteristics collected included gender, educational level, professional title, years of experience, and their degree of familiarity with frailty concepts. The authority of experts was represented by the authority coefficient (Cr), which comprises two factors: the familiarity degree (Cs) and the judgment basis (Ca). The familiarity degree (Cs) was self-reported by experts on a 5-point scale: very familiar (1.0), moderately familiar (0.75), generally familiar (0.5), somewhat familiar (0.25), and unfamiliar (0). The judgment basis (Ca) was determined based on four aspects: practical experience (0.8), theoretical analysis (0.6), knowledge of domestic and international peers (0.4), and intuitive judgment (0.2). The combined authority coefficient (Cr) was calculated using the formula: Cr = (Cs + Ca)/2. A Cr value above 0.70 was considered acceptable, indicating a reliable level of expert authority. The inquiry process The expert questionnaire was distributed via e-mail, and experts were requested to return their responses within two weeks. In the first round, experts were provided with an initial item pool ( n In the second round, the revised list of items, along with a summary of the previous round’s ratings and expert comments, was sent back to the same panel. Based on expert recommendations from Round 1, two new items pertaining to Physical Function and one new item related to Other Function were added to the questionnaire. Consequently, a total of 30 items were included in the Round 2 questionnaire for further consultation. The complete item pool for Delphi Round 2 evaluation is presented in Supplementary Table S2. Experts were asked to re-rate the updated items and to indicate their agreement with the overall item set. Items were screened using the boundary value method, evaluating each based on its mean importance score, full-score frequency, and coefficient of variation (CV). The threshold for retention was set at the mean score or full-score frequency exceeding the boundary value, calculated as the mean minus one standard deviation. Items meeting these criteria were retained for the final frailty screening scale(see Table S4 for details). For the coefficient of variation, the threshold was set as “mean plus standard deviation,” and items with CV values below this threshold were considered acceptable. Experts were also invited to provide final suggestions on the structure and applicability of the scale. Two rounds of expert consultation were conducted in total, with an interval of over 20 days to minimize recall bias and ensure independent judgment across rounds. The final 22-item frailty screening scale is presented in Supplementary Table S3. Data analysis All collected data were double-entered and verified by two independent researchers (Qin Wang and Yuhui Zhang), and analyzed using Microsoft Excel 2016 and SPSS 22.0 software. The descriptive statistics of expert characteristics were presented as frequencies and percentages (%).The Cr, CS, and Ca values were calculated as previously described. Item scores were summarized using means and CVs. The degree of agreement among experts was measured by Kendall’s coefficient of concordance (W), which ranges from 0 to 1, with higher values indicating better consistency in expert opinions. A non-parametric test of Kendall’s W was performed at a significance level of α = 0.05. Results Basic information of experts A total of 16 experts were invited to participate in this study, and all 16 completed both rounds, with a response rate of 100% for each round. Table 1 1 Table 1 Basic information of experts ( N Working group characteristics Value Specialists. n Geriatric specialists 6(37.50%) Cardiology specialist 1(6.25%) Evidence-based medicine specialist 1(6.25%) General medical practitioner 2(12.50%) Family medicine doctor 6(37.50%) Healthcare setting. n Academic hospital 8(50.00%) General hospital 2(12.50%) Community health service centers 6(37.50%) Years of clinical experience. n < 10 2(12.50%) 10 ~ 15 2(12.50%) 16 ~ 20 1(6.25%) 21–25 4(25.00%) 26–30 4(25.00%) > 30 3(18.75%) Years of clinical experience, mean ± SD 22.56 ± 8.69 Degree. n Doctoral degree 7(43.75%) Master’s degree 2(12.50%) Bachelor’s degree 7(43.75%) Degree of expert authority All 16 invited experts completed both rounds of consultation, resulting in a 100% response rate for each round, indicating a high degree of expert engagement. Following the first round, two experts provided three additional recommendations, leading to a refined set of items. After the second round, no further recommendations were made, signifying the convergence of expert opinions. The mean familiarity degree (Cs) was 0.77 and 0.75 for the two rounds, respectively. The mean judgment basis (Ca) was 0.86 in the first round and 0.87 in the second, while the combined authority coefficient (Cr) was 0.82 and 0.81, respectively. Degree of concentration of expert opinions In this study, the importance scores from the two rounds of expert consultation ranged from 3.53 to 4.69 and 3.29 to 4.75, respectively. The coefficient of variation (CV) was calculated only for the second round of the Delphi survey. In the physical function subscale, the item with the highest CV was item P6, while the lowest was item P3. In the psychological function subscale, item M2 had the highest CV and item M3 the lowest. For the social function subscale, item S1 showed the highest CV, and item S3 the lowest. In the other domains, the highest CV was observed for item E7, and the lowest for item E8.(see Table 2 Table 2 The results of expert opinion coordination coefficient First-round Second-round The number of items 27 30 Coordination coefficient 0.22 0.40 χ 2 89.27 185.76 P < 0.001 < 0.001 Kendall’s W values of two rounds of expert correspondence were 0.22 and 0.40, respectively, with statistical significance ( P Changes of frailty screening scale for community-dwelling older adults in China Items were screened using the boundary value method. As a result, three items (P3, P4, and P6) were removed from the physical function subscale; one item (M2) was removed from the psychological function subscale; two items (S1 and S2) were removed from the social function subscale; and two items (E2 and E7) were removed from the other domains. A total of 22 items across four dimensions were retained to form the final version of the frailty screening scale, as shown in Table 3 Table 3 Final items of the frailty screening scale for community-dwelling older adults Category Items Physiological performance 1. Conduct a 4-meter walking test at usual walking speed. The cut-off value is determined based on the weakening phenotype standard: (1) Male: height ≤ 173 cm − 7 s; height > 173 cm − 6 s (2) Female: height ≤ 159 cm − 7 s; height > 159 cm − 6 s 2. Perform a grip strength test on the dominant hand using a grip device for three trials and record the maximum value. The cut-off value is determined based on the weakening phenotype standard: (1) Male: BMI ≤ 24–29 kg; BMI 24.1–26–30 kg; BMI 26.1–28–31 kg; BMI > 28–32 kg (2) Female: BMI ≤ 23–17 kg; BMI 23.1–26–17.3 kg; BMI 26.1–29–18 kg; BMI > 29–21 kg 5. Which physical activities do you engage in weekly, such as walking, jogging, swimming, cycling, etc.? How many hours per week do you spend on each activity? Calculate the daily energy expenditure based on the answers. The cut-off value is determined based on the debilitating phenotype standard: (1) Male − 380 kcal; Female − 270 kcal 7. Have you experienced a reduction in food intake in the past three months due to poor appetite, digestive problems, chewing difficulties, or swallowing difficulties? 8. Which of the following tasks can you complete independently without assistance from others? The use of assistive resources, such as crutches or walking aids, is considered independent: (1) Putting on or taking off clothes (2) Using the bathroom (3) Performing heavy physical work, such as cleaning windows and mopping the floor (4) Climbing two flights of stairs (5) Walking 1000 m 9. Are there any physical conditions that limit your ability to leave your home? 10. Have you been diagnosed with more than five diseases by a medical professional, including but not limited to: (1) Hypertension (2) Diabetes (3) Cancer (excluding skin cancer) (4) Chronic lung disease (5) Heart failure (6) Angina pectoris (7) Asthma (8) Arthritis (9) Stroke (10) Nephrosis 11. Have you experienced fatigue in the past month? Have you been unable to complete tasks that you were previously able to accomplish? 12. Have you experienced difficulty in recovering your strength fully after fatigue in the past month? Mental health 1. In the previous month, have you experienced a loss of self-confidence and felt incapable of achieving anything? 3. Have you experienced feelings of nervousness or anxiety in the previous month? 4. In the previous month, have you engaged in any activities that used to bring you joy, but no longer do? Social vulnerability 3. Do you live alone? If so, do you miss the presence of family and friends? 4. Do you have someone in your life whom you trust completely? 5. Are you satisfied with your community and living environment? 6. Do you frequently experience feelings of rejection from others? 2. Do you manage your own bank account? 3. Have you experienced a fall in the past year? Other function 4. Do you have concerns about falling while walking? 6.How many types of medication are you currently taking? 7. Do you frequently forget to take your prescribed medication? 8. Are you able to prepare your own meals three times a day? Discussion Frailty is a multidimensional syndrome increasingly recognized in geriatric care, yet current screening tools vary widely in structure, diagnostic performance, and contextual suitability [ 2 34 35 36 37 38 39 40 33 1 Fig. 1 Flowchart of the Delphi Process for Developing Frailty Screening Scale for Community-Dwelling Older Adults in China Based on the findings of the systematic review, we extracted high-frequency and high-relevance items from existing tools to develop the initial list for the Delphi process. The Delphi panel consisted of 16 experts with diverse backgrounds, including geriatricians, clinical epidemiologists, public health researchers, and community healthcare practitioners. Most participants were senior academics with over 10 years of experience in their respective fields, contributing to the credibility and representativeness of the consensus process. After two rounds of expert consultation, a total of 22 items were retained. These items broadly covered major frailty domains, including physical function, nutrition, psychological well-being, functional status, fall risk, multimorbidity, polypharmacy, medication adherence, and social vulnerability. Most of the retained items also appeared frequently in the reviewed tools, indicating good consistency between literature-based evidence and expert clinical judgment. In the setting of community screening, it may be argued that a high degree of specificity is important because those who have been screened positive will be referred for more detailed assessment, and a low false positive value is important in avoiding waste of resources [ 41 The FRAIL scale is widely used due to a high degree of specificity, yet primarily focus on physical deficits and comorbidity, with limited coverage of psychological and social domains [ 42 43 44 33 41 The Groningen Frailty Indicator (GFI), though broader in dimensional coverage, is relatively lengthy and relies heavily on subjective responses, reducing feasibility in fast-paced community workflows [ 45 46 48 More recently, the Chinese Frailty Screening Scale (CFSS-10) was developed based on the ICOPE framework and tested among community-dwelling older adults in Shanghai [ 24 24 49 In contrast, the FSS was specifically designed for Chinese community screening through a two-phase process: evidence-based item selection via meta-analysis and local contextual refinement through a Delphi expert panel. It integrates physical, psychological, nutritional, functional, and social domains within a concise 22-item format, balancing multidimensional assessment with ease of administration. The item was simplified and tested for clarity among older adults, ensuring linguistic accessibility. Owing to this comprehensive, culturally-informed item generation and evidence-based development, the FSS is theoretically designed to possess superior overall structural validity compared to some existing scales [ 24 25 32 40 This study has several notable strengths. To our knowledge, it is the first to systematically incorporate findings from diagnostic accuracy meta-analyses into the item selection process for frailty tool development. This evidence-based approach ensured that the resulting item pool was grounded in empirical performance rather than only expert opinion. In addition, the Delphi panel included experts from geriatrics, clinical epidemiology, public health, and community care, providing a multidisciplinary perspective. The response rate across both Delphi rounds was 100%, enhancing the credibility and consistency of the consensus process. Nonetheless, several limitations should be acknowledged. Firstly, while our Delphi consensus process was rigorous, it did not directly incorporate insights from frontline community health workers or the older adults themselves. These stakeholders’ perspectives could enhance the understanding of real-world feasibility and acceptability. Secondly, despite its evidence-based development, the FSS has not yet undergone comprehensive real-world validation. Validation studies, including direct comparisons with established frailty scales, are necessary to confirm its effectiveness and utility. Finally, the FSS was developed based on data from specific regions or populations, which may not fully reflect the socioeconomic, cultural, and regional diversity across China, such as differences between rural and urban communities or among ethnic minority groups. This constraint may hinder the scale’s generalizability and nationwide applicability. Further studies are needed to assess its performance across varied Chinese populations to enhance its broader relevance. Conclusions This study developed a frailty screening scale tailored for community-dwelling older adults in China, using a two-phase approach that integrated diagnostic accuracy evidence and expert consensus. While preliminary findings suggest its potential as an effective screening tool, further validation is needed to confirm its reliability, predictive validity, and applicability across diverse Chinese populations. Therefore, we encourage this promising tool to be used for further verification and generalization. Supplementary Information Below is the link to the electronic supplementary material.  Supplementary Material 1  Supplementary Material 2  Supplementary Material 3  Supplementary Material 4 Publisher’s note Springer Nature remains neutral with regard to jurisdictional claims in published maps and institutional affiliations. Acknowledgements We would like to express our sincere gratitude to all experts who participated in the Delphi process for their valuable time and insights. Additionally, we would like to express our appreciation to the staff of the China